rce World of Gay Asian Drag -- t16 “The Reason You Can Suck a Dick Is Because Some Fem Once Got Beaten Up, Right?” A Case Study of Gender, Race, and Sexuality for Latinx Queer Men -- t17 Radical Cheerbois: Genderqueer Bodies Performing Queer Femininity -- tPart 5 Male Femininities and Intimacies -- tIntroduction -- t18 Unloved -- t19 Assume the Position: Bottom-Shaming among Black Gay Men -- t20 Are Polyamorous Men Embodying Male Femininity? -- t21 Male Femininity as Spirituality among Radical Faeries -- tPart 6 Male Femininities and Institutions -- tIntroduction -- t22 Funeral Rights -- t23 When Our Boys Wished to Be Girls: A Retrospective Look at Parenting Gender-Nonconforming Young Boys -- t24 Negotiating Masculinity in the Fire Service: Accessing Brotherhood or Subverting Gender Norms -- t25 Resisting Femininity in Responsible Fathering: Men and the Gendering of Care in US Fatherhood Policy -- tConclusion: Male Femininities and Dismantling the Binaries and Boundaries of Gender -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Contributors -- tAbout the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInnovative essays that explore how men perform femininity and what femininity looks like without womenWhat counts as “male femininity”? Is it simply men behaving in effeminate ways or is it the absence of masculinity? Male Femininities presents a nuanced, critical collection of essays that highlight the extent to which male femininities are neither an imitation of femaleness nor an emptying of masculinity. These innovative essays focus on both gay and straight men, and transmasculine and genderqueer people in their construction and performance of femininity, thereby revealing the possibilities that open up when we critically examine femininity without women. Male Femininities asks, What does femininity look like for men?The contributors—highly regarded scholars and rising stars—cover a range of topics, including drag queens, cosmetic enhancements, trans fertility, and gender-non-conforming childhoods. Male Femininities illuminates what happens when we decouple femininity from female bodies and how even the smallest cracks and fissures in the normative order can disrupt, challenge, and in some cases reaffirm our existing sex-gender regime. This volume pluralizes the concept of male femininities and leads readers through an exploration of how gender, sex, and sexuality are manifested in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEffeminacy. 0aFemininity. 0aMasculinity. 0aMenxIdentity. 0aSex role. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aHalberstam.  abody technology.  aeffeminacy.  afemininity.  agender binary.  agender inequality.  agender revolution.  agender.  ahealth.  ahegemonic masculinity.  aheteronormativity.  ahomosexuality.  amale femininity.  amale pregnancy.  aqueer theory.  aqueer.  asexualities.  asocial constructionism.1 aAdair, Joshua G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Rusty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaver, Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkowitz, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkowitz, Dana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBishop, Katelynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonvissuto, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouncilor, Kc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDansky, Steven F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrensaft, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l